5. Mimi codec (Kyutai / Moshi authors) — CC-BY 4.0 attribution
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
The Mimi RVQ codec integrated by the M3-06 `mimi_rvq` operator
(crates/vokra-ops/src/mimi_rvq.rs) is distributed by Kyutai as part of the
Moshi project under the Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International
license (CC-BY 4.0). Commercial use is permitted; attribution is required.

  Mimi Codec
  Copyright (c) Kyutai / Moshi authors
  Licensed under CC-BY 4.0
  Source: https://github.com/kyutai-labs/moshi
          https://huggingface.co/kyutai/mimi

The Vokra runtime implements the Mimi decode side (residual codebook
lookup + FP32 residual sum) from published documentation; upstream Mimi
weights are loaded through the standard GGUF path and are subject to the
M2-13 compliance gate (`AttributionRequired` license class).

M4-05 additionally implements the Mimi *neural chain* natively — the
encoder (audio -> RVQ codes: SEANet conv stack + bottleneck transformer +
RVQ quantize) and the neural decoder (RVQ features -> 24 kHz PCM) in
crates/vokra-models/src/mimi/ (shared by Sesame CSM, M4-05, and Moshi,
M4-06). This attribution covers the Kyutai Mimi weights consumed by those
components as well: encoder, quantizer codebooks, and neural decoder
weights all originate from the same CC-BY 4.0 Kyutai release named above.

M4-06 additionally implements the Moshi language model natively — the
Helium temporal transformer, the per-step-weight depformer, the
inner-monologue text stream, and the full-duplex session runtime in
crates/vokra-models/src/moshi/ (whisper.cpp-style re-implementation from
the published kyutai-labs/moshi sources; no upstream code is copied).
The Moshi LM weights (kyutai/moshiko-pytorch-bf16 `model.safetensors`)
are likewise Kyutai CC-BY 4.0 — this attribution covers them, and the
runtime additionally surfaces a deployer-facing attribution string
(GGUF `vokra.provenance.attribution` -> `Session::attribution` /
`vokra_model_attribution` / the vokra-cli banner) so downstream
applications can meet the display obligation (FR-MD-09).

This attribution is separate from the EU AI Act §50 AI-generated-audio
disclosure obligation. The disclosure obligation is enforced at output
time by the runtime's `WatermarkConfig` API and is orthogonal to this
codec-level credit.

